'''Kristoffer Vassbakk Köpp Ajer''' (born 17 April 1998) is a Norwegian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays either as [[centre-back]] or [[right-back]] for {{English football updater|Brentfor}} club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] and the [[Norway national football team|Norway national team]]. Ajer has previously played for [[IK Start|Start]] in the [[Tippeligaen]] and [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in the [[Scottish Premiership]], where he also had a loan spell with [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]].<ref name="Henderson">{{Cite web |last=Henderson |first=Mark |date=16 June 2016 |title=New Celtic signing reveals his favoured position {{!}} CelticFC {{!}} First Team News |url=https://www.celticfc.com/news/10710 |access-date=2 October 2021}}</ref>

==Early and personal life==
Kristoffer Vassbakk Ajer was born in [[Rælingen]], [[Akershus]] County in [[Norway]] on 17 April 1998.<ref>{{Soccerway|id=347247|accessdate=2 October 2021}}</ref> In his younger years he participated in athletics, handball and ice hockey before ending up playing football.

As a youth player he originally started his footballing career at [[Rælingen FK]] before joining [[Lillestrøm SK]] when he was eleven years old.<ref name=rb>{{cite web |url=http://www.rb.no/lsk-magasinet/article7660433.ece |title=Drømmen oppfylles i feil drakt |work=Romerikets Blad |date=26 October 2014}}</ref> He was eventually picked up by IK Start in 2014, which marked the start of his professional footballing career as a result of his parents moving to the city of [[Kristiansand]] on the Southern coast of Norway.<ref name=rb/>

While playing professionally for [[IK Start]], he attended ''Kristiansand Katedralskole Gimle'' (High School) where he was known as a very conscientious and diligent student receiving a total of 18 straight A's. He attributed this to his strong competitive instinct and self-discipline, as well as the support from his teachers and parents and the fact that he values having a good education outside of his footballing career.<ref>{{Cite web |last=AS |first=TV 2 |date=24 May 2018 |title=Kristoffer Ajer med 18 seksere på vitnemålet |url=https://www.tv2.no/a/9876766/ |access-date=2 October 2021 |website=TV 2}}</ref> Ajer originally planned enrolling at the Faculty of Medicine at the [[University of Oslo]] while simultaneously playing football professionally, but he has since put those plans on hold.<ref>{{Cite web |title=– At jeg fikk 18 seksere er mest honnør til skolen, ikke meg |url=https://www.tv2.no/v/1681425/ |access-date=2 October 2021 |website=TV 2}}</ref> On the reasons why he excelled as a footballer, he attributed this to his early physical development, strength and maturity:

{{blockquote|<small>''I feel like I've been pretty lucky in my career. I was developing physically from a very early age: When I was six years old I was two heads taller than the rest of the players on the field. After a match where we won 30–0, I accounted for 26 goals. I remember I was refused to play the next matches of the tournament if I could not prove my age. After this, my mother always had my passport with her when I was playing football matches.''<ref name="morgendagenshelter">{{Cite web |title=Kristoffer Ajer |url=https://morgendagenshelter.no/rollemodell/kristoffer-ajer |access-date=2021-10-02 |website=morgendagenshelter.no}}</ref></small>}}

He is also a mentor/ambassador for the [[Equinor]] campaign for future athletes, entrepreneurs and talents in Norway called ''Morgendagens Helter'' ("Heroes of Tomorrow").<ref name="morgendagenshelter" />

==Club career==
===Start===
He made his professional debut for Start on 19 July 2014 in a 2–1 win against [[FK Bodø/Glimt|Bodø/Glimt]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnsen|first=Sture|title=Start-Bodø/Glimt: 2–1 (0–0)|url=http://www.ikstart.no/match-reports/article/1hdgjf7t9iox9197l24c0rnj7o/title/kamp-start-bodoglimt|access-date=15 February 2016|work=IK Start|date=19 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223071010/http://www.ikstart.no/match-reports/article/1hdgjf7t9iox9197l24c0rnj7o/title/kamp-start-bodoglimt|archive-date=23 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>

At 16 years of age, Ajer captained Start in a 1–1 draw against Lillestrøm on 7 April 2015, becoming the youngest ever footballer to captain a team in the [[Tippeligaen]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tottenham and Liverpool chasing Norwegian wonderkid Kristoffer Ajer|url=http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2015/06/06/report-tottenham-and-liverpool-chasing-norwegian-wonderkid-krist/|access-date=15 February 2016|work=HITC Sport|date=7 June 2015|first=Matthew|last=Nash|archive-date=6 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106012643/http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2015/06/06/report-tottenham-and-liverpool-chasing-norwegian-wonderkid-krist/|url-status=dead}}</ref> While playing for IK Start he played both as a central midfielder, but was gradually placed as a central defender.

===Celtic===
In early January 2016, Ajer had a one-week trial with Scottish club [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/35239213|title=Kristoffer Ajer: Celtic take Norwegian midfielder on trial|publisher=BBC|date=5 January 2016|access-date=6 June 2020}}</ref> On 17 February 2016, he signed a four-year contract with Celtic and joined the club in June 2016 for a fee which could rise up to £650,000.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Kristoffer Ajer signs four-year deal with Celtic |url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/10068 |website = celticfc.net |access-date=17 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = The hard bargaining that brought Kristoffer Ajer to Celtic |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/14281132.The_hard_bargaining_that_brought_Kristoffer_Ajer_to_Celtic |website = The Herald|location=Glasgow |date=16 February 2016 |access-date=3 October 2017}}</ref> He was loaned to [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] in January 2017 and returned to his parent club to become a mainstay in central defence.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38687981 |title=Kilmarnock sign Celtic's Kristoffer Ajer on loan |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=20 January 2017 |access-date=20 January 2017}}</ref> On 14 May 2018, Ajer penned a new four-year deal with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44110323|title=Kristoffer Ajer: Celtic defender signs new four-year contract|date=14 May 2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=15 May 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> On 30 August, Ajer scored his first goal for Celtic in a 3–0 win against [[FK Sūduva]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=12 September 2019|title=Griffiths makes it a century of goals as Celts beat Suduva {{!}} CelticFC {{!}} Match Report|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/14865|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912222255/http://www.celticfc.net/news/14865|archive-date=12 September 2019|access-date=2 October 2021}}</ref>

On 24 October 2019, Ajer made his 100th appearance in all competitions for Celtic's first team in a [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] match against [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]].

===Brentford===
[[File:Kristoffer Ajer 02082025 (4).jpg|thumb|upright|Ajer signing autographs after a [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] match in 2025.]]
On 21 July 2021, Ajer completed a move to [[Premier League]] club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] on a five-year deal for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Brentford complete signing of Kristoffer Ajer from Celtic|url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2021/july/brentford-complete-signing-of-kristoffer-ajer-from-celtic/|access-date=21 July 2021|website=brentfordfc.com|language=en-gb}}</ref> He made his Premier League debut on 13 August 2021 in a 2–0 win against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. He scored his first goal for Brentford against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] on 7 May 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Brentford hammer Southampton to leave Ralph Hasenhuttl facing fans' fury|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/brentford-southampton-result-final-score-hasenhuttl-b2073813.html|access-date=20 August 2023|website=The Independent|language=en-gb}}</ref>

On 21 November 2023, Ajer signed a new deal with Brentford until the summer of 2028, with the club keeping an option to extend his contract for a further season. He scored his second goal against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 16 March 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 November 2023 |title=Ajer signs new Brentford contract |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/en/news/article/first-team-kristoffer-ajer-signs-new-brentford-contract |access-date=23 November 2023 |website= |publisher=Brentford F.C. |language=en-gb}}</ref>

==International career==
On 13 March 2018, Ajer received his first call-up to the Norwegian senior squad for friendly matches against [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]] and [[Albania national football team|Albania]],<ref>{{Cite news|first=Christer|last=Madsen|title=Her er troppen til kampene mot Australia og Albania|url=https://www.fotball.no/landslag/norge-a-herrer/2018/her-er-troppen-til-kampene-mot-australia-og-albania/|website=[[Norwegian Football Federation]]|date=13 March 2016|access-date=16 March 2016|language=no}}</ref> debuting in the former match to honour his late grandfather.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Tore Ulrik|last=Bratland|title=Holdt avtale med død bestefar i debuten|url=https://www.dagbladet.no/sport/holdt-avtale-med-dod-bestefar-i-debuten/69647055|website=[[Dagbladet]]|date=23 March 2018|access-date=24 March 2018|language=no}}</ref>

